Part I - (Loan Data from Prosper)¶

by (Awofolaju Afusat)¶

Introduction¶

This dataset contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This dataset consists of 113,937 rows/loans and 81 columns/variables. Prosperscore is dependents on most of the other variables and most of the independent variables are of float datatypes. Some variables such as ProsperScore(Ordinal), employmentStatus(Norminal), and IncomeVerifiable are categorical.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

Area of interest is checking for the variables that will affect the properScore(which is our dependent variable) of a borrower.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

IncomeRange, IncomeVerifiable, EmploymentStatus, Recomendations, OnTimeProsperPayments and isBorrowerHomeOwner are some of the variables ProsperScore depends on.

# function to plot bar chart
def hist(DataFrame, variable, x_label, title):
#Add figure size
    plt.figure(figsize = [14, 6])
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[1]
    sb.countplot(data=DataFrame, x=variable, color  = base_color );
    plt.xlabel(x_label)
    plt.title(title, fontsize=16)
    plt.show()

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The plot distribution of ProsperScore shows that the most people that obtain loan have ProsperScore between 4 and 8. Also, it was shown that people with IncomeRange of '$25,000 and $74,999' receive most loans. Those that pay their loans on time have high tendency of getting another loan if requested.

The plot distribution shows that IncomeVerifiable is a great determinant of loan collection. It was clearly seen that people with a verifiable source of income receive loans that those that their income isn't verifiable. We could also see that an individaul chance of getting loan is higher when employed than others. Whereas recommendations do not have significant effect on loan collection.

Lastly, a home owner having a higher percentage of getting loan compared to those that are not home owners is not that significant based on the plot distribution made.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Yes, i replaced ProsperScore values greater than ten with 10, fill the null values and re-arranged the plot distribution of EmploymentStatus as they were not in standard form.

def bivariateBar(variable, hueVar):
    plt.figure(figsize = [12, 6])
    sb.countplot(data=df, x=variable, hue=hueVar);
    plt.show()
def bivariateBar_II(variable, hueVar):
    plt.figure(figsize = [12, 6])
    sb.countplot(data=df, x=variable, hue=hueVar);
    variable= variable.replace("_"," ") # replace _ with space
    plt.show()

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Based on the exploration done, it can be seen that those with verifiable income have high ProsperScore than those whose income can't be verified. Also, the ProsperScore of borrowers who are home owners is higher than those who are not. Lastly, most of the people that are employed are home ownwers. All these independent variables are great factors that influence the outcome of the dependent variable.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Yes, there are interesting relationships between the other variables. From the scatter plot shown above, it can be seen that those that are gainfully employed will make the loan payments on time. Surprisingly, from the violin plot above, being a home owner does not guarantee that the borrower will pay the loan on time as the violin plots are almost the same.

Multivariate Exploration¶

In [91]:
#Function to plot Multivariate Variables.
def multVariate(x,y,hue):
    plt.figure(figsize = [12, 5])
    ax = sb.pointplot(data = df, x = x, y = y, hue = hue,
                      dodge = True, linestyles = "")
    ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(),rotation = 90);
    
#Function to plot Multivariate Variables.
def multVariate_II(x,y,hue):
    plt.figure(figsize = [12, 5])
    ax = sb.stripplot(data = df, x = x, y = y, hue = hue,
                      dodge = True, order=None, size = 2, jitter = 0.35 )
    x = x.replace("_"," ") # replace _ with space
    y = x.replace("_"," ")
    hue = x.replace("_"," ")
    #title
    plt.title(f''''Average {y} by {x} and {hue} '''.title(), fontsize =15, weight="bold")
    #Xlabel
    plt.xlabel(x.title(), fontsize = 12, weight = 'bold')
    plt.ylabel('frequency'.title(), fontsize = 12, weight = 'bold')
    
    #despine
    sb.despine()

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

It can be observed from the graph plotted that, those who are employed and are home owners tend to pay their loan on time. Also, those who are gainfully employed and work full time with a verifiable source of income have higher prosperScore.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Yes, it can be seen from the point plot above that those there are not employed but have verifiable source of income have high prosper score.

Conclusions¶

The main goal of my exploration analysis is to determine if some independent variables(EmploymentStatus, IncomeVerifiable, OnTimeProsperPayments, IsBorrowerHomeowner and Recommendations) i chose will affect/influence the dependent variable(ProsperScore). I plotted different kinds of graphs ranging from univariate to bivariate and multivariate where it was deduced that once you have a verifiable source of income, whether you are employed or not, you are going to get a loan. Surprisingly, being a home owner doesn't mean the person is going to pay the loan on time. Also, those that pay their loans on time are always given and have high prosper score.
